\section{The presemifield property}
\label{lformsection}

We consider the multiplication $x\circ y$ in $B(2,m,s,l,t),$ see
(\ref{circgeneralprodequ}) or (\ref{circFlevelprodequ}). Let $x*y=x\circ{\overline}{y}.$ Clearly

\begin{Theorem}
\label{lformchar2theorem}
$B(2,m,s,l,t)$ in Definition \ref{Bfamilyintrodef} is indeed a presemifield (of order $2^{2m}$).
\end{Theorem}
\begin{proof}
For $l=0$ this is Theorem \ref{multKnuthchar2theorem}. Let $l\not=0,$
assume $x*y=0,xy\not=0.$
The imaginary part shows $y=e{\overline}{x}$ for $e\in L.$
The real part factorizes:
$(e^{{\sigma}}+le)T(C_1x{\overline}{x}^{{\sigma}}+C_2x^{{\sigma}+1})=0.$ The first factor is nonzero by the condition on
$l,$ the non-vanishing of the trace term is the second condition of
Theorem \ref{multKnuthchar2theorem}.
