 Observe that the condition on $l$ in Definition \ref{Bfamilyintrodef} can be met for $l\not=0$ only if
$\gcd(m,s)\not=1.$ In particular $m$ has to be a composite number. The smallest choice is therefore
$m=4$ and the resulting semifields have order $2^8.$

\begin{Corollary}
\label{nofieldcor}
$B(2,m,s,l,t)$ where $l\not=0, s\notin\lbrace 0,m\rbrace$ is not isotopic to a field.
\end{Corollary}
\begin{proof}
The restriction to $L$ is $x*y=(h_1+h_2)(xy^{{\sigma}}+lx^{{\sigma}}y).$
When $l\not=0$ and ${\sigma}$ is not the identity on $L,$ then
this is isotopic to a generalized twisted
field.
\end{proof}










